          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>Which factor is the PRIMARY reason the resting membrane potential of a neuron is</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Which factor is the PRIMARY reason the resting membrane potential of a neuron is close to −70 mV?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>High membrane permeability to potassium through leak channels, allowing K⁺ efflux</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. At rest, the membrane is far more permeable to K⁺ than Na⁺. K⁺ leak channels let K⁺ exit down its concentration gradient, leaving the interior negative — close to the K⁺ Nernst potential.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The Na⁺/K⁺-ATPase directly generating most of the voltage across the membrane</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The pump is electrogenic but contributes only a few millivolts. Its main role is maintaining the ion gradients that the leak channels then use.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Continuous inward leak of chloride ions along its concentration gradient</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Chloride plays a minor role in most neurons at rest. The dominant determinant is potassium permeability through leak channels.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Open voltage-gated sodium channels allowing a small steady Na⁺ influx</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Voltage-gated Na⁺ channels are closed at rest. A small Na⁺ leak exists, but it only offsets the K⁺-driven potential slightly.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Remember: the membrane at rest is mainly permeable to K⁺. K⁺ efflux through leak channels creates the negative interior; the pump maintains the gradient but does not directly set the voltage."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done. The resting potential is essentially a potassium diffusion potential, shifted slightly by Na⁺ leak and maintained by the Na⁺/K⁺ pump."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
