          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>In myasthenia gravis, muscle weakness occurs because autoantibodies target which</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>In myasthenia gravis, muscle weakness occurs because autoantibodies target which structure at the neuromuscular junction?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Voltage-gated calcium channels on the presynaptic axon terminal</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>These are the target in Lambert-Eaton myasthenic syndrome, not myasthenia gravis. The effect there is reduced ACh release.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Nicotinic acetylcholine receptors on the motor end-plate</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Autoantibodies destroy postsynaptic nicotinic receptors, reducing the end-plate potential below the safety factor and causing fatiguable weakness.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Acetylcholinesterase in the synaptic cleft</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>AChE is inhibited by drugs like neostigmine and organophosphates, not by autoantibodies in myasthenia gravis.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>SNARE proteins involved in vesicle fusion</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>SNAREs are cleaved by botulinum toxin, which blocks ACh release. Myasthenia gravis attacks the postsynaptic receptors.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Myasthenia gravis is a postsynaptic disorder — autoantibodies against nicotinic ACh receptors. Lambert-Eaton, botulinum, and AChE inhibitors affect different parts of the junction."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Exactly. Loss of functional nicotinic receptors shrinks the end-plate potential. Neostigmine helps by letting ACh linger and find the remaining receptors."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
