          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>During skeletal muscle excitation-contraction coupling, calcium released from th</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>During skeletal muscle excitation-contraction coupling, calcium released from the sarcoplasmic reticulum triggers contraction by binding to which molecule?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Myosin light chain, activating cross-bridge cycling directly</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>That is the mechanism in smooth muscle, via calmodulin and myosin light chain kinase. Skeletal muscle uses a different calcium sensor.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Tropomyosin, physically displacing it from actin</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Tropomyosin does move off the binding sites, but not because calcium binds it directly. Calcium binds troponin, which then shifts tropomyosin.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Troponin C, causing tropomyosin to shift and expose actin binding sites</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Ca²⁺ binds troponin C, the troponin complex shifts tropomyosin off actin, and myosin heads can then attach and pivot.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The ryanodine receptor, opening it to release more calcium</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The ryanodine receptor releases calcium; it is not the calcium-binding sensor that initiates cross-bridge cycling. That role belongs to troponin C.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "In skeletal muscle, calcium binds troponin C. This shifts the troponin-tropomyosin complex off actin, exposing binding sites for myosin heads."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done. Troponin C is the calcium switch in skeletal and cardiac muscle. Smooth muscle uses calmodulin instead."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
