          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>Why can cardiac muscle NOT be tetanised, unlike skeletal muscle?</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Why can cardiac muscle NOT be tetanised, unlike skeletal muscle?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Cardiac muscle lacks sarcoplasmic reticulum, so calcium cannot be recycled quickly enough</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Cardiac muscle has a sarcoplasmic reticulum and uses calcium-induced calcium release. The barrier to tetanus is electrical, not a calcium recycling problem.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Cardiac action potentials have a prolonged plateau phase, producing an absolute refractory period that lasts almost the entire contraction</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. The long plateau — driven by L-type Ca²⁺ channels — keeps the cell refractory throughout the contraction, so summation and therefore tetanus are impossible.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Cardiac cells are electrically isolated from each other, preventing the spread of repetitive stimuli</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The opposite is true. Gap junctions at intercalated discs electrically couple cardiac cells so that excitation spreads easily.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Cardiac muscle relies entirely on aerobic metabolism, which cannot sustain the rapid firing needed for tetanus</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Aerobic dependence matters for fatigue resistance, but the reason tetanus is impossible is the long absolute refractory period, not energy supply.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The key is the prolonged cardiac action potential. Its plateau (from L-type Ca²⁺ channels) gives an absolute refractory period nearly as long as the contraction itself, so a second contraction cannot summate."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Exactly. The long plateau and matching refractory period are a protective mechanism — if the heart tetanised, it would stop pumping blood."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
